'''Clinical professor''', also known as '''professor of practice''', is an [[Academic rank|academic appointment]] made to a member of a profession who is associated with a [[university]] and engages in practical instruction of [[professional student]]s.<ref>[http://www.mcg.edu/faculty/facman/fadpt/clinicaladjunct.html CLINICAL AND ADJUNCT FACULTY APPOINTMENT POLICY] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101213071737/http://www.mcg.edu/faculty/facman/fadpt/clinicaladjunct.html |date=December 13, 2010 }}, [[Medical College of Georgia]] Faculty Manual. October 26, 2004. </ref> Titles in this category may include Clinical Instructor, Assistant Clinical Professor, Associate Clinical Professor, and Clinical Professor.<ref name = "ucla" /> Clinical professorship generally does not offer a "[[tenure track]]", but can be either full or part-time, and is typically noted for its emphasis on practical skills training as opposed to theoretical matters. Thus, most members of such faculty are expected to have considerable practical experience in their respective fields of expertise; unlike with most other faculty, this is deemed at least as important as educational credentials.<ref name = "ucla">{{cite web|url=https://www.apo.ucla.edu/policies-forms/the-call/professorial-series/clinical-professor-series-volunteer-series|title=Clinical professor series: Volunteer series|work=UCLA Academic Personnel Office|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> For administrative purposes, some universities classify such a designation as equivalent to "[[adjunct professor]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ap.ucsb.edu/policies.and.procedures/red.binder/sections/%5B5_20%5D%20Professor%20of%20Practice.pdf|title=Professor of Practice|work=University of California, Santa Barbara|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> Clinical professors may be salaried or may teach as a volunteer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/handbook/appointments-and-promotions/classification-of-ranks-and-titles/|title=Classification of Ranks and Titles|work=Faculty Handbook|publisher=Boston University|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref>
In the field of medicine, full clinical professors generally work full time at the medical college and its affiliated hospitals, while assistant clinical professors are part time with their full practice elsewhere, with little involvement in medical education; the assistant clinical professor position may be almost entirely honorary.<ref>{{cite web |title=What Makes A “Top” Doctor |url=http://www.castleconnolly.com/AmExPDFs/ATopDoctor.pdf |publisher=Castle Connolly |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703233751/http://www.castleconnolly.com/AmExPDFs/ATopDoctor.pdf |archivedate=3 July 2018 |pages=8-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=M.L.B. Medical Adviser Falsifies Resume |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/29/sports/baseball/mlb-medical-adviser-falsifies-resume.html |date=March 29, 2005 |language=en |quote=But he is an assistant clinical professor, a lower-ranking and honorary position that is held by thousands of doctors, a medical college official said.}}</ref> In Canada, doctors who teach are called "[[preceptor]]s".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mercer |first1=C |title=Family medicine faces shortage of doctors willing to teach. |journal=CMAJ : Canadian Medical Association journal <nowiki>=</nowiki> journal de l'Association medicale canadienne |date=28 May 2018 |volume=190 |issue=21 |pages=E666 |doi=10.1503/cmaj.109-5604 |pmid=29807944 |pmc=5973894}}</ref>
==Examples of clinical professor== *Clinical Professor of Medicine *Clinical Professor of Nursing *Clinical Professor of Psychology *Clinical Professor of Law *Clinical Professor of Business *Clinical Professor of Economics *Clinical Professor of Pharmacy *Professor of Professional Practice (various professional fields)
