{{Orphan|date=December 2013}}

The '''Ikaria Study''' is a small-scale survey by  the [[University of Athens]] School of Medicine of the [[diet (nutrition)|diet]] and lifestyle of  [[Greek people]] over age 80 on the island of Ikaria.<ref name="DAN BUETTNER">{{cite news  
| last=  BUETTNER
| first=  DAN 
| url=  https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/28/magazine/the-island-where-people-forget-to-die.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0
| title=  The Island Where People Forget to Die
| publisher=  [[nytimes.com]]
| date=  October 24, 2012
| accessdate= November 12, 2012
}}</ref> The study found that the Ikarian diet includes [[olive oil]], [[red wine]], [[fish]], [[coffee]], [[herbal tea]], [[honey]], potatoes, [[garbanzo bean]]s, [[black-eyed pea]]s, [[lentils]], and a  limited amount of meat, sugar and [[dairy products]],  except [[goat milk]].<ref name="DAN BUETTNER" />

The data showed that people on Ikaria were  reaching the age of 90 at 2.5 times the rate Americans do, and that  Ikarian men   are almost four times as likely as American men to reach age 90.<ref name="DAN BUETTNER" />

